<h2> Nutcracker Design </h2>
<p> <strong>Task:</strong> Design a nutcracker that can crack open a macademia nut by hand using a simple lever. </p>

<p> <strong> Plan: </strong> 
Examine FBD of a nutcracker then take the moment about the front point
</p>

<p> <strong> Given:</strong> 
<ul>
  <li>Nut diameter: 2 cm</li>
  <li>Grip force: 45 kg</li>
  <li>Required cracking force: 222.18 kg</li>
  <li> Assume nut is placed at 3cm</li>
</ul></p>

<p><strong>Diagram of nutcracker </strong></p>
<img src="{{ '/assets/images/Nutcracker_FBD.png' | relative_url }}" alt="Nutcracker Diagram" width="800">

<p> <strong> Calculations: </strong> 
\[
\sum \vec{M}_O = \vec{r}_1 \times \vec{F}_m - \vec{r}_2 \times \vec{F}_a = 0
\]
\[
0 = (3)(222.18) - r_2(45)
\]
\[
r_2=14.812
\]
</p>

<p>The nutcracker will be 14.812cm long with the nut placed at 3cm. By examining similar right triangles, we can find that the arms will open to a height of 9.874cm at the end. This would be a very large nutcracker and would be very difficult to use. If a linear actuator was used instead, the size of the nutcracker can be shrunk much farther down. </p>

<p><strong>Mini Industrial Actuator:</strong> 330lb=149.72kg</p>
<p>
\[
\sum \vec{M}_O = \vec{r}_1 \times \vec{F}_m - \vec{r}_2 \times \vec{F}_a = 0 
\]
\[
0 = (3)(222.18) - r_2(149.72)
\]
\[
r_2=4.451
\]
</p>

<p> Using the linear actuator allows the arm to be much shorter, but it will still be somewhat wide due to the actuator having a 5in maximum length. However, since it is still much smaller than the original design, it is a much more viable option. </p>